update_self_containment (chapter-scale): The input is a FULL CHAPTER. Can
it stand on its own as a unit of reading? A new reader picking up this
chapter — without having read the prior chapters — should be able to
follow who, where, what-is-at-stake, and close on a beat that feels like
an ending, not a dangling comma.

0.0 = unreadable without prior-chapter memory. Opens mid-action with
      unexplained proper nouns; ends mid-scene with no resolution.
0.3 = partially legible. Some orientation is present but most threads are
      dangling on entry. A careful reader can reconstruct context but
      the chapter does not help.
0.5 = readable but lossy. A new reader will miss emotional stakes
      without prior context; key NPCs are named but their significance
      is not re-surfaced.
0.7 = opens with enough orientation (who / where / what-is-at-stake) to
      ground a new reader and closes with a clear chapter-beat. Load-
      bearing names are re-established by action or dialogue at least
      once, not assumed.
1.0 = fully self-contained chapter. Opening scenes plant necessary
      context by action and dialogue, not exposition dump. Closing beat
      lands without requiring prior-chapter callbacks. A new reader can
      follow the entire arc and feel its stakes; standing threats and
      promises are re-surfaced at the moment they matter in this chapter.

Note: self-containment is NOT the same as "no serial continuity." A
chapter can reference recurring characters, carry a multi-chapter plot
arc, and still score 0.9 if it re-establishes those elements in-text
rather than relying on the reader's memory.

Anchors:
  HIGH: a chapter that opens with the protagonist arriving at a known
        town, uses a first-scene dialogue to re-establish who is with
        them and what they want, and ends on a concrete decision.
  MID : a chapter that assumes you remember a name mentioned once, three
        chapters ago, and closes on a reveal that trades on that memory.
  LOW : a chapter that opens "She did it anyway" and closes "and that was
        when everything changed" referring to unstated prior events.

Return a single score in [0.0, 1.0] and one sentence of rationale calling
out opening context legibility and closing-beat completeness.
